{"audits":[{"idea_id":"621b91e4991a67b9","agent":"codex","title":"The Interface Invariant Model","exact_claim":"Cross-tradition convergence may come from recurring human interface invariants such as attention, identity, salience, agency, and boundary-making, rather than from discovery of the same hidden metaphysical substance.","claim_units":["Independent traditions can converge without sharing a metaphysical object.","The shared structure is the human interface of attention, identity, salience, agency, and boundaries.","Witness-consciousness, emptiness, nondual awareness, wu wei, and surrender may report alterations of that interface.","The model preserves comparative value while blocking naive perennialism."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, Max Muller translation, https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/sbe15070.htm","SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, Thanissaro Bhikkhu translation, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html"],"structural_observation":"The pair supports only part of the model. Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 repeatedly places an inner ruler within earth, beings, organs, mind, and knowledge, then identifies this as Self and immortal. SN 22.59 examines form, feeling, perception, fabrications, and consciousness, then rejects each as mine, self, or what I am because each is inconstant and not masterable. Both disturb ordinary identity and boundary-making, but their final authority structure diverges sharply: one licenses an unobjectifiable Self, the other de-authorizes ownership of all aggregates including consciousness.","secondary_literature_gap":"Search found strong near-neighbors in constructivist mysticism, Stace and Forman on pure consciousness, enactivism, Metzinger's minimal phenomenal experience work, self-model theory, and neurophenomenology. No source found the exact five-part interface list as a comparative-spirituality rubric, but the structural move is heavily precedented.","risk_of_overread":"High. The model can silently translate ontological, devotional, ritual, and soteriological claims into cognitive-interface language. It may explain reports, but it does not by itself interpret traditions on their own terms."},"literature_search_queries":["interface invariants attention identity salience agency boundary-making spiritual traditions convergence","Thomas Metzinger minimal phenomenal experience pure awareness witness consciousness","Steven Katz Language Epistemology and Mysticism constructivism pure experience","Varela Thompson Rosch embodied mind Buddhism enactive self no self","Robert Forman pure consciousness event comparative mysticism"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Mysticism, https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mysticism/","overlap":"Very close at the level of the perennialist versus constructivist problem. The entry covers Stace's universal introvertive mysticism, Forman's pure consciousness event, and Katz's claim that conceptual schemes shape mystical experience.","difference":"The Lumenary model substitutes a cognitive-interface invariant list for the older universal core or constructivist framing.","novelty_impact":"High reduction. The core alternative to metaphysical sameness is already central in comparative mysticism."},{"source":"Gamma and Metzinger, The Minimal Phenomenal Experience questionnaire, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8279394/","overlap":"Close. The MPE-92M factors include wakeful presence, emptiness and non-egoic self-awareness, mental agency, and witness consciousness, which overlap strongly with the proposed interface variables.","difference":"The paper is a phenomenological questionnaire and does not make a full cross-tradition convergence theory for spiritual motifs such as wu wei and surrender.","novelty_impact":"High reduction for the invariant list. Some originality remains in using it as a comparative-audit frame."},{"source":"Varela, Thompson, and Rosch, The Embodied Mind, MIT Press overview, https://mitpress.mit.edu/9780262529365/the-embodied-mind/","overlap":"Close. Enactivism already reframes cognition as world-disclosure through embodied action and was built in dialogue with Buddhist no-self and mindfulness.","difference":"The Interface Invariant Model names a smaller audit-ready set of invariants and compares several traditions rather than building one enactive cognitive-science program.","novelty_impact":"Moderate to high reduction. The world-disclosure move is old, but the Lumenary operationalization may be useful."},{"source":"Metzinger, Minimal phenomenal experience, https://philpapers.org/rec/METMPE","overlap":"Close. Metzinger explicitly studies pure awareness, self-luminosity, sakshin, turiya, rigpa, and minimal phenomenal selfhood as a route to modeling consciousness.","difference":"Metzinger is not primarily making a comparative religion publication rule for convergence claims.","novelty_impact":"High reduction for the consciousness and self-model components."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike Stace, Forman, Katz, Varela, Thompson, Rosch, or Metzinger, this idea proposes a Lumenary comparison unit in which apparent spiritual convergence is scored by recurring changes to attention, identity, salience, agency, and boundary-making, without inferring one shared metaphysical object.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Theistic surrender and grace traditions, for example Christian apophatic prayer or Islamic tawakkul, may treat relation to God as irreducible, not as de-emphasis of agency or boundary-making.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"If the practitioner says the core invariant is not an altered interface but a real Other who initiates and judges the transformation, the model becomes a reduction rather than an interpretation.","confidence_effect":"Lowers confidence from candidate-discovery range to novel-synthesis range."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"Cross-tradition reports of witness, emptiness, surrender, and wu wei should cluster by shifts in attention, agency, salience, identity, and boundary experience even when doctrinal vocabulary differs.","expected_observation":"Blind coders should reliably tag these interface variables in practitioner reports better than chance, while also preserving doctrinal differences.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Reports cluster mainly by tradition-specific doctrine, devotional object, or teacher vocabulary, with weak cross-tradition interface structure.","test_surface":"Qualitative coding of meditation, prayer, and contemplative-inquiry interviews across Advaita, Theravada, Daoist, Sufi, and Christian sources."},{"if_model_is_right":"Low-metaphysical comparison using interface variables should predict practice similarities better than metaphysical labels such as Self, emptiness, God, or nature.","expected_observation":"Practice instructions with similar attention and agency moves should produce similar near-term phenomenological reports even when ontology differs.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Metaphysical training context predicts reports more strongly than interface variables do.","test_surface":"Matched practitioner interviews before and after narrowly specified practices."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Comparative religion scholars","Contemplative-science researchers","Advaita teachers","Buddhist meditation teachers","Daoist practice teachers","Christian contemplatives","Sufi teachers"],"questions":["Do you already compare traditions by shifts in attention, agency, salience, identity, and boundaries?","Does this frame reveal anything about practice that your tradition's own vocabulary does not already capture?","Where would this model reduce or distort the meaning of your practice?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"Practitioners and scholars say this is just constructivism, enactivism, MPE research, or perennialism rewritten in cognitive-interface language.","answers_that_support_contribution":"They say the invariant list changes how they compare practices, predicts misunderstandings, or helps distinguish phenomenological overlap from metaphysical agreement."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Human-computer interaction and virtual reality","structural_translation":"Interface invariants become attention routing, agency attribution, salience marking, avatar identity, and boundary control.","prediction":"Immersive systems that alter these variables should generate report patterns resembling mild contemplative shifts, without requiring spiritual metaphysics.","would_count_against_it":"Altering interface variables changes task performance but does not produce predictable shifts in self, agency, salience, or boundary reports."},"originality_status":"novel_synthesis","confidence":0.78,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.52,"source_reliability":0.74,"counterargument_quality":0.86},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.76 to about 0.52. The idea is a useful synthesis of comparative mysticism, constructivism, enactivism, self-model theory, and minimal phenomenal experience research, not a discovered structure yet.","next_loop_instructions":["Do not publish this as a metaphysical claim.","Build a five-variable coding sheet and test it on narrow primary-text pairs before using broad tradition names.","Add a devotional anomaly set: grace, surrender, bhakti, tawakkul, and Christian apophasis.","Separate interface change, doctrinal interpretation, and claimed ontological referent in all future records."]},{"idea_id":"d92d2f0f6455ac53","agent":"codex","title":"Translation Strain as a Load Test for Convergence","exact_claim":"When traditions seem to converge, the productive datum is the exact distortion required to translate one claim into the other; low strain may indicate stable overlap, while high strain should be labeled analogical productivity rather than evidence.","claim_units":["Similarity should not be treated as direct evidence of sameness.","The comparison unit is the translation distortion, not the broad resemblance.","Bends, drops, and reweightings should be named explicitly.","Low strain and high strain should have different publication labels."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html","Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7, Tat tvam asi, https://shlokam.org/texts/Chandogya-6-8-7/"],"structural_observation":"The pair illustrates the method but does not make the method original. SN 22.59 refuses ownership and self-identification across all aggregates, including consciousness. Chandogya 6.8.7 uses the recurring formula that the subtle essence is the Self and that the student is that. Any claim that both say the same thing requires bending the status of consciousness, the final pedagogical aim, and the authority of identity-language. This is exactly what comparison theory, constructivism, and homeomorphic equivalence already train scholars to notice.","secondary_literature_gap":"The previous Lumenary audit already found Smith, Freiberger, Panikkar, Katz, Sharf, Clooney, Sandmel, and translation studies as close prior art. No stronger search result made the load-test label itself important enough to rescue novelty.","risk_of_overread":"Moderate. The method may make every failed comparison look productive. Without a stopping rule, strain becomes a way to publish any analogy."},"literature_search_queries":["Jonathan Z Smith comparison redescription rectification difference similarity religion","Oliver Freiberger comparative methodology selection description juxtaposition redescription rectification","Raimon Panikkar homeomorphic equivalence comparative religion","Steven Katz constructivism mystical experience no pure experience","translation shifts untranslatability religious concepts comparative theology"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Previous Lumenary audit, Convergence as Translation Strain, Not Evidence Weight, reviews/originality/2026-05-26-convergence-as-translation-strain-not-evidence-weight-eef7e83c44da8b8c.json","overlap":"Near exact. The prior audit already states that convergence should be evaluated by claim-level bends, drops, and additions rather than evidential weight.","difference":"This candidate adds the phrase load test and a low-strain versus high-strain scoring suggestion.","novelty_impact":"Decisive reduction. As a new Lumenary finding, this is already present."},{"source":"Oliver Freiberger, Elements of a Comparative Methodology in the Study of Religion, https://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/9/2/38","overlap":"Very close structurally. Freiberger already treats comparison as an explicit method with selection, description, juxtaposition, redescription, rectification, and theory formation.","difference":"The candidate narrows this into a scoring tool for spiritual convergence and names distortions as strain.","novelty_impact":"High reduction. The method is an operational adaptation, not a discovery."},{"source":"Jonathan Z. Smith, In Comparison a Magic Dwells, https://classics.osu.edu/sites/classics.osu.edu/files/Magic_Dwells.pdf","overlap":"Very close. Smith warns that scholars project perceived similarity into objective connection and argues for disciplined difference, redescription, and rectification.","difference":"The candidate turns Smith's comparative caution into a publication gate and strain vocabulary.","novelty_impact":"High reduction."},{"source":"Raimon Panikkar, homeomorphic equivalence glossary, https://raimon-panikkar.org/english/gloss-homeomorphic.html/","overlap":"Close. Homeomorphic equivalence already compares concepts by functional role within distinct systems while preserving non-identity.","difference":"The load-test frame adds explicit accounting of what is bent, dropped, or reweighted.","novelty_impact":"Moderate to high reduction."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike Smith, Freiberger, Panikkar, Katz, Sharf, or the earlier Lumenary strain audit, this candidate offers only the load-test metaphor and a possible low-strain versus high-strain publication rule. That difference is too small to count as a new finding.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Comparisons where high strain is still historically causal, for example Buddhist and Advaita terms shaped by centuries of polemic and borrowing.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"High strain does not necessarily mean merely analogical productivity. A high-strain term may still be historically entangled, polemical, or deliberately inverted.","confidence_effect":"Lowers confidence in the low-strain/high-strain scoring rule."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"A strain rubric should change publication decisions compared with ordinary resemblance scoring.","expected_observation":"Some high-similarity pairs should be downgraded because central meanings must be discarded, and some low-verbal-similarity pairs should be retained because functional role survives.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"The rubric produces the same decisions as ordinary expert judgment while adding only terminology.","test_surface":"Blind A/B comparison of 20 cross-tradition comparison records."},{"if_model_is_right":"Experts should agree on named distortions when the rubric is clear.","expected_observation":"Independent coders should identify similar lexical, practice-context, metaphysical, ethical, and phenomenological strains.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Coder agreement remains low, or identified strains track coder tradition rather than text features.","test_surface":"Inter-rater reliability test with Buddhist, Vedanta, Christian, and Sufi scholars."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Comparative religion scholars","Comparative theologians","Religious translators","Buddhist studies scholars","Advaita Sanskritists","Contemplative teachers with cross-training"],"questions":["Do you already ask what must be bent, dropped, or reweighted before accepting a convergence?","Does a strain sheet change your judgment, or only rename your existing scholarly method?","What comparison should be rejected even though its strain is interesting?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"Practitioners and scholars say this is standard comparative method, homeomorphic equivalence, translation studies, or the prior Lumenary strain audit.","answers_that_support_contribution":"They say the load-test scoring rule produces reproducible decisions that ordinary comparison theory does not produce."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Legal translation and comparative law","structural_translation":"A legal term survives translation only if jurisdictional function, authority, remedy, and procedure are preserved or explicitly marked as distorted.","prediction":"A strain rubric should predict where apparent equivalents such as trust, equity, right, or due process mislead across legal systems.","would_count_against_it":"Legal translators already use equivalent tools with no added decision value from the strain rubric."},"originality_status":"known","confidence":0.9,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.22,"source_reliability":0.82,"counterargument_quality":0.9},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.78 to about 0.22. This is already present in the prior Lumenary originality audit and strongly anticipated by comparative-method literature.","next_loop_instructions":["Merge this record into the existing translation-strain finding instead of publishing it as new.","If retained, define the stopping rule for when high strain means reject rather than analogically productive.","Add historical-dependence fields so borrowing, polemic, and shared modern discourse are not mistaken for independent convergence.","Require inter-rater testing before giving the rubric public-claim weight."]},{"idea_id":"5a05c720a5039323","agent":"codex","title":"Residue Policy in Negative Self-Practice","exact_claim":"The precise Advaita-Buddhist comparison should ask what each path permits to remain after negation: Brihadaranyaka preserves an unobjectifiable seer-knower, while SN 22.59 withholds authorization from any aggregate including consciousness.","claim_units":["Both traditions unsettle identification with ordinary experience.","The key comparison unit is residue policy after negation.","Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 permits an unobjectifiable seer-knower as remainder.","SN 22.59 applies not-self analysis to consciousness and does not authorize an aggregate remainder.","The strain is not just self versus no-self, but whether de-objectification licenses residue."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/sbe15070.htm","SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html"],"structural_observation":"The contrast is textually real but needs narrowing. Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 is not merely a meditation report after negation. It is part of the antaryamin sequence, where the inner ruler is within cosmic elements, beings, organs, mind, and knowledge. SN 22.59 is not a general ontology of every possible remainder; it is an analysis of the aggregates as unfit for appropriation. The proposed residue policy works if it is limited to the comparison between authorized Self-language and non-appropriation of aggregate consciousness.","secondary_literature_gap":"Close prior art includes Advaita-Buddhism comparison, Shankara on witnessing consciousness, Buddhist not-self strategy debates, and scholarship on consciousness without content. The specific phrase residue policy was not found, but the structural contrast is well known.","risk_of_overread":"Moderate to high. The idea risks importing later Advaita sakshin doctrine into an older Upanishadic passage and treating one early Buddhist discourse as all Buddhist self-analysis."},"literature_search_queries":["Advaita Buddhism witness consciousness not-self comparison Atman anatman","Shankara witness consciousness deep sleep Buddhist no self comparison","Thanissaro not-self strategy no self aggregates consciousness","Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 unseen seer no other knower","SN 22.59 consciousness not self aggregate"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Shankara, https://seop.illc.uva.nl/entries/shankara/","overlap":"Very close for the Advaita side. It presents witnessing consciousness as distinct from mind and cognition, self-illuminating, and continuous through waking, dreaming, and deep sleep.","difference":"The Lumenary idea compares this with early Buddhist aggregate analysis and names the comparison residue policy.","novelty_impact":"High reduction for the preserved witness component."},{"source":"David Loy, Enlightenment in Buddhism and Advaita Vedanta, https://buddhism.lib.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-AN/26715.htm","overlap":"Close. Loy directly compares nirvana and moksha, objectless consciousness, Atman-Brahman, and Buddhist cessation, including the difficulty of calling nondual awareness consciousness.","difference":"Residue policy is a more operational audit field than Loy's broader comparative essay.","novelty_impact":"Moderate to high reduction."},{"source":"Thanissaro Bhikkhu, The Not-Self Strategy, https://www.buddhistinquiry.org/article/the-not-self-strategy/","overlap":"Close anomaly and prior art. Thanissaro frames not-self as a liberation strategy rather than a metaphysical claim that there is no self.","difference":"The Lumenary idea focuses on whether a remainder is authorized in a specific comparison, not on the full Pali Canon hermeneutic.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction and significant constraint."},{"source":"Matthias Rose, Prakasa: Advaitic consciousness as presence, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11097-020-09690-2","overlap":"Close. It explains Advaita's deconstruction of self-objectification and the claim that consciousness is self-disclosing and never an object.","difference":"It does not turn the comparison with Buddhism into a residue-authorization rubric.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike standard self versus no-self comparisons, this idea proposes a smaller operational field: after ordinary identifications are negated, record whether the tradition authorizes, tests, refuses, or leaves undecided any remainder.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Dhammatalks' note to SN 22.59 points to texts about a kind of consciousness outside the aggregate range of all, and Thanissaro argues not-self is strategic rather than a denial of all remainder.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"If early Buddhist materials allow an unestablished or unobjectified dimension beyond aggregate consciousness, then SN 22.59 cannot be used as simple no-remainder policy. It only blocks aggregate appropriation.","confidence_effect":"Reduces confidence and requires the residue field to distinguish aggregate remainder from non-aggregate liberation language."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"Practice manuals should diverge at the point where attention tries to identify awareness itself.","expected_observation":"Advaita instructions should more often say rest as, recognize, or abide as awareness, while vipassana instructions should more often say observe knowing, consciousness, or awareness as arising, passing, empty, or not-self.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Manuals across both traditions use the same instruction at that point, or both authorize and de-authorize awareness in similar ways.","test_surface":"Coding Ramana, Shankara-lineage, Mahasi, Thai Forest, and early sutta practice instructions."},{"if_model_is_right":"Practitioners trained in different residue policies should differ in post-negation interpretation even when phenomenological reports are similar.","expected_observation":"After reporting contentless or objectless awareness, Advaita-trained practitioners should more often use Self or awareness-as-ground language, while Buddhist-trained practitioners should resist ontological upgrade.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Training tradition does not predict interpretation, or reports do not pass through any recognizable residue question.","test_surface":"Structured interviews after self-inquiry, vipassana, and open-awareness retreats."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Advaita Vedanta teachers","Sanskritists","Theravada meditation teachers","Pali scholars","Buddhist modernist teachers","Dual-trained practitioners"],"questions":["In your practice, what is the student told to do when only awareness or knowing seems to remain?","Is awareness recognized as Self, investigated as another phenomenon, or left strategically unclassified?","Does residue policy name a real practice difference or only redescribe familiar doctrine?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"They say this is the standard Atman/anatta distinction or a familiar Advaita versus Buddhist contrast with a new label.","answers_that_support_contribution":"They say the residue field clarifies specific teacher instructions and prevents false nondual equivalence."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Psychotherapy and metacognitive training","structural_translation":"After negative inquiry dissolves ordinary roles and narratives, a method either authorizes a stable observing self, recursively investigates it, or brackets it pragmatically.","prediction":"Therapies that strengthen observer-self language should differ from therapies that deconstruct observer-self language in how clients report agency and identity after decentering.","would_count_against_it":"Observer-self and no-self style protocols yield identical reports and clinical outcomes with no distinct residue policy effects."},"originality_status":"extended","confidence":0.79,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.57,"source_reliability":0.74,"counterargument_quality":0.88},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.76 to about 0.57. The contrast is familiar, but the residue-authorization field is a useful operational refinement.","next_loop_instructions":["Test the rubric on Brihadaranyaka 2.4, 2.5, 3.7.23, SN 22.59, and SN 22.95 before broader claims.","Separate antaryamin cosmology from later Advaita witness practice.","Add values for aggregate remainder, non-aggregate remainder, strategic silence, and undecidable.","Do not publish without Pali and Sanskrit term checks."]},{"idea_id":"3763a79cf5b05610","agent":"codex","title":"Residual Burden of Proof After Negation","exact_claim":"The decisive difference between Upanishadic witness language and early Buddhist not-self may be an inference policy after negation: whether non-objectifiability shifts the burden toward an unobjectifiable seer or keeps the burden against any self-claim.","claim_units":["The key difference is inferential policy, not only doctrine of self versus no-self.","Upanishadic negation can be read as licensing an unobjectifiable seer-knower.","SN 22.59 can be read as requiring any proposed remainder to undergo the same not-self test.","Comparison should score inference authorization separately from residue content."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 2.4.5-14, Maitreyi dialogue, https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/sbe15061.htm","SN 22.95 Pheṇa Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_95.html"],"structural_observation":"The inference-policy frame is plausible but partly anachronistic. Brihadaranyaka 2.4 commands seeing, hearing, reflecting on, and knowing the Self, then asks how the knower could be known when all is Self. This is not simply an inference from failed objectification. SN 22.95 compares consciousness to a magic trick and asks what substance could be found in it, but it functions as contemplative disenchantment rather than a formal burden-of-proof rule. The model is strongest if it is stated as an interpretive reconstruction of argument-behavior, not as the texts' explicit logic.","secondary_literature_gap":"Important near-neighbors include Advaita self-luminosity and pramana debates, Buddhist not-self strategy, Madhyamaka refusal of extremes, and modern philosophy of consciousness. The audit did not reach enough Sanskrit or Pali commentarial material to confirm the inference-policy claim historically.","risk_of_overread":"High. Advaita sources often say consciousness is immediately self-disclosing, not inferred. Buddhist sources may frame not-self as pragmatic release, not epistemic burden allocation."},"literature_search_queries":["Advaita self-luminosity consciousness not inferred pramana witness","Brihadaranyaka how know the knower Maitreyi self proof","SN 22.95 consciousness magic trick empty void without substance","Buddhist not-self strategy burden of proof self claim","Madhyamaka neither self nor no self inferential policy"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Matthias Rose, Prakasa, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11097-020-09690-2","overlap":"Very close and partly corrective. The article says Advaita treats consciousness as directly self-disclosing, not as a posit inferred from other evidence.","difference":"The Lumenary idea compares the implicit permission rule with early Buddhist not-self analysis.","novelty_impact":"High reduction and strong anomaly. The model must not say Advaita merely infers the witness."},{"source":"Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Shankara, https://seop.illc.uva.nl/entries/shankara/","overlap":"Close. Shankara's witness accounts for memory and deep sleep continuity and resists the claim that absence of object implies absence of consciousness.","difference":"The Lumenary idea reframes this as burden allocation after negation.","novelty_impact":"High reduction for the Advaita side."},{"source":"Thanissaro Bhikkhu, The Not-Self Strategy, https://www.buddhistinquiry.org/article/the-not-self-strategy/","overlap":"Close for the Buddhist side. It denies that the Buddha's teaching should be reduced to a metaphysical no-self thesis and treats not-self as a strategy.","difference":"The Lumenary idea treats the strategy as an inference policy against remainder claims.","novelty_impact":"Moderate to high reduction."},{"source":"Nagarjuna, Mulamadhyamakakarika 18.6, English text example, https://docslib.org/doc/1736275/mulamadhyamakakarika-by-nagarjuna","overlap":"Close at the level of refusing both self and no-self as final views.","difference":"The Lumenary model compares Upanishadic and early Buddhist rules, while MMK offers a Madhyamaka deconstruction of the polarity itself.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction and important third-case constraint."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike ordinary residue-policy language, this idea isolates the rule that decides whether a proposed remainder is allowed to count. Its originality depends on proving that such a rule is operative in texts or practice, not merely useful for modern analysis.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Advaita denies that the Self is inferred, it is treated as immediate self-disclosure and the basis for using means of knowledge at all.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"If the witness is not inferred from negation, then the model's burden-of-proof language misdescribes the Advaita side. The comparison becomes a modern epistemological reconstruction, not a textual discovery.","confidence_effect":"Substantially lowers confidence in the exact claim."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"Texts and commentaries should contain repeatable rule-like moves after negation.","expected_observation":"Advaita commentaries should use non-objectifiability to block denial of Self, while Buddhist commentaries should apply impermanence, conditionality, or not-self analysis to any proposed witness-like remainder.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Commentaries treat these as direct revelation, scriptural authority, or therapeutic instruction with no identifiable inference policy.","test_surface":"Close reading of Shankara's Brihadaranyaka and Brahma Sutra commentaries, Pali commentaries, and modern teacher manuals."},{"if_model_is_right":"Dual-trained practitioners should be able to identify the moment where inference policy changes practice interpretation.","expected_observation":"They report that one instruction says recognize the unobjectifiable, while another says investigate the recognizer or do not appropriate it.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"They experience no such rule shift and describe the difference only as language or community doctrine.","test_surface":"Interviews with practitioners trained in both Advaita self-inquiry and Theravada vipassana."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Advaita scholars","Pali scholars","Madhyamaka scholars","Theravada teachers","Ramana-style self-inquiry teachers","Dual-trained contemplatives"],"questions":["Does your tradition treat the witness as directly recognized, inferred, scripturally revealed, or pragmatically useful?","When negation leaves only knowing, what rule says whether that knowing can be called Self?","Does inference authorization change practice instructions, or is it just modern analytic vocabulary?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"Experts say Advaita self-luminosity and Buddhist not-self strategy already cover this, or that burden-of-proof language is alien to the texts.","answers_that_support_contribution":"Experts say the field distinguishes direct recognition, scriptural assertion, inference, pragmatic bracketing, and recursive testing in ways existing self/no-self comparisons blur."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Philosophy of perception","structural_translation":"After all perceptual contents are doubted, a system either treats the remaining subject-pole as certain, recursively doubts it, or refuses the question.","prediction":"The same inference-policy typology should classify Cartesian, phenomenological, Buddhist, and eliminativist responses to the subject of experience.","would_count_against_it":"The typology collapses because debates turn on ontology or method rather than any burden rule."},"originality_status":"extended","confidence":0.7,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.48,"source_reliability":0.72,"counterargument_quality":0.9},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.79 to about 0.48. This is a refinement of residue policy and overlaps strongly with Advaita self-luminosity, Buddhist not-self strategy, and Madhyamaka refusal of extremes.","next_loop_instructions":["Rewrite the claim as an interpretive reconstruction unless commentarial evidence proves explicit inference rules.","Add separate rubric values: direct recognition, scriptural assertion, inference, pragmatic bracketing, recursive testing, and undecidable.","Close-read Shankara on self-luminosity before saying Advaita infers the witness.","Use MMK 18.6 as an anomaly, not as support for a simple Buddhist refusal policy."]},{"idea_id":"d6fee3a4a4435d8c","agent":"codex","title":"Remainder Pressure as the Hidden Variable in Self-Negation","exact_claim":"The bridge between Upanishadic witness language, early Buddhist not-self analysis, and modern consciousness research is remainder pressure: the felt or conceptual demand to posit a final subject after object-like contents have been negated.","claim_units":["Self-negation can generate pressure to posit a final subject.","Traditions manage this pressure differently: ontologize, recursively analyze, bracket phenomenologically, or model it cognitively.","The pressure is separable from the inference policy used to interpret it.","Modern self-modeling and meta-awareness research can test the pressure without settling metaphysics."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/sbe15070.htm","SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html"],"structural_observation":"The texts show divergent management of remainder, but they do not clearly show a felt pressure. Brihadaranyaka supplies a seer-knower through a cosmological and theological sequence. SN 22.59 applies a disciplined not-self template to aggregates. The pressure variable is therefore not directly textual. It is an interpretive bridge from these texts to practice reports and cognitive science.","secondary_literature_gap":"The search found close components in minimal phenomenal experience, self-model theory, attention and agency factors, pure consciousness debates, and nirodha research. No exact prior phrase remainder pressure appeared, but the mechanisms are not new enough to call a discovery without empirical coding.","risk_of_overread":"High. The model may psychologize metaphysical claims and may invent a universal pressure that not all practitioners experience."},"literature_search_queries":["remainder pressure final subject after negation self inquiry Buddhism Advaita","minimal phenomenal experience witness consciousness non-egoic self-awareness Metzinger Gamma","consciousness without content Advaita Buddhism dreamless sleep cessation","nirodha samapatti cessation consciousness Laukkonen Slagter","self-model theory meditation no-self witness awareness"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Gamma and Metzinger, MPE-92M, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8279394/","overlap":"Close. The questionnaire maps pure-awareness reports using factors such as witness consciousness, mental agency, non-egoic self-awareness, wakeful presence, and self-knowledge.","difference":"It does not frame these as pressure to posit a final subject after negation.","novelty_impact":"High reduction for the empirical-adjacent mechanism."},{"source":"Josipovic, Nondual Awareness and Minimal Phenomenal Experience, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7473343/","overlap":"Close. It connects nondual awareness, pure consciousness, rigpa, sakshin, turiya, and minimal phenomenal experience across contemplative traditions.","difference":"The Lumenary idea adds a variable for how systems interpret the seeming remainder.","novelty_impact":"Moderate to high reduction."},{"source":"Laukkonen et al., Cessations of consciousness in meditation, https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0079612322001984","overlap":"Close anomaly and test surface. Cessation research treats reports of absent consciousness as scientifically investigable and potentially disruptive to metaphysical views of self.","difference":"The candidate uses cessation as a test of remainder pressure rather than as a state taxonomy.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction."},{"source":"Metzinger, Minimal phenomenal experience, https://philpapers.org/rec/METMPE","overlap":"Close. Metzinger uses pure awareness reports as an entry point for minimal model explanation and self-model analysis.","difference":"The Lumenary idea compares management policies across spiritual texts and practice reports.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike MPE, pure consciousness, or self-model literature, this idea names the pressure to promote a residual subject as a variable distinct from the tradition's final interpretation of that pressure.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Nirodha samapatti and cessation reports, where practitioners report a discontinuity or absence of consciousness rather than a pressure to posit an enduring witness.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"If advanced practice can end reported consciousness without producing a subject-remainder pressure, the pressure is not an invariant. It may be tradition-specific, stage-specific, or retrospectively constructed.","confidence_effect":"Lowers confidence from candidate-discovery to novel-synthesis."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"Remainder pressure should be detectable in reports before doctrinal interpretation is applied.","expected_observation":"Practitioners should describe a pull toward phrases such as something remains, knowing remains, no one owns it, or cannot locate the knower before choosing metaphysical language.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Reports move directly into doctrine or simple absence without any intermediate pressure category.","test_surface":"Micro-phenomenological interviews after self-inquiry, vipassana, open monitoring, and cessation-adjacent retreats."},{"if_model_is_right":"Training style should shape how the pressure is resolved, not whether the pressure can arise at all.","expected_observation":"Similar reports of content reduction should be resolved as Self, no-self, bracketed awareness, or self-model artifact depending on training context.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Training context predicts the entire phenomenology so strongly that no shared pressure stage can be identified.","test_surface":"Longitudinal study of practitioners cross-trained in Advaita and Buddhist methods."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Micro-phenomenology interviewers","Contemplative neuroscientists","Advaita self-inquiry practitioners","Theravada insight practitioners","Dzogchen and Mahamudra teachers","Meditation researchers studying cessation"],"questions":["After negating contents, do practitioners actually report a pressure to posit a final subject?","Can that pressure be distinguished from doctrine, teacher suggestion, and retrospective explanation?","Does naming remainder pressure change how you guide students who reify awareness?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"Practitioners say the pressure is just craving, selfing, witness fixation, or self-modeling, all already named in their fields.","answers_that_support_contribution":"They say the term helps separate the arising of a reportable residue from the later move that turns it into Self, no-self, or cognitive artifact."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Artificial intelligence interpretability","structural_translation":"When a model's outputs are stripped of content-level explanations, observers may feel pressure to posit a hidden agent, controller, or center behind behavior.","prediction":"Users should attribute a central agent more strongly when visible content and local mechanisms are made opaque but coherent behavior remains.","would_count_against_it":"Opacity reduces agent attribution or produces only uncertainty, with no pressure toward hidden-subject explanations."},"originality_status":"novel_synthesis","confidence":0.72,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.61,"source_reliability":0.7,"counterargument_quality":0.87},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.84 to about 0.61. The phrase is useful and may be generative, but it synthesizes known work on pure awareness, witness consciousness, self-modeling, and cessation.","next_loop_instructions":["Define observable markers of remainder pressure before using it as an explanatory variable.","Code practitioner reports for pressure, interpretation, teacher prompt, and retrospective doctrinal framing.","Treat nirodha and dreamless sleep as anomaly cases.","Do not infer a universal phenomenological stage until micro-phenomenological interviews support it."]},{"idea_id":"a441942e48bd643a","agent":"claude","title":"The Inferential Gap: Atman and Anatta as Competing Policies for Objectless Awareness","exact_claim":"The Atman/anatta contradiction is best understood as a disagreement about inferential authority: what objectless awareness permits one to conclude about what persists when experience has no object.","claim_units":["Advaita and Buddhism may share a phenomenological ground in de-objectification practice.","The dispute concerns what objectless awareness authorizes, not only what exists.","Advaita fills the gap with a transcendental inference to Atman/Brahman.","Buddhism refuses the inference and treats filling the gap as renewed clinging or wrong view.","The translation strain lives in inferential policy more than phenomenology."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["Mandukya Upanishad verse 7, https://www.shlokam.org/text/mandukya-upanishad.htm","SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html"],"structural_observation":"Mandukya 7 negates inward, outward, mixed, massed, cognitive, and non-cognitive descriptions, but still names the fourth as nondual Self to be realized. SN 22.59 does not discuss objectless awareness in Mandukya's terms. It examines each aggregate and rejects identification with consciousness because it is inconstant, stressful if clung to, and not masterable. The candidate's shared phenomenology is therefore not established by these primary texts. The inferential gap is a plausible comparative reconstruction, but it is not directly shown without practice reports or commentarial bridges.","secondary_literature_gap":"The idea cites strong sources, but the audit found close prior art in Codex residue-policy work, Advaita self-luminosity scholarship, Stace/Forman/Katz interpretation debates, Loy's Buddhism and Advaita comparison, and Madhyamaka self/no-self refusal. More work is needed in Sanskrit, Pali, Gaudapada, Shankara, Abhidhamma, Yogacara, and Madhyamaka commentaries.","risk_of_overread":"High. The claim that both traditions share phenomenology but differ in inference may be too clean. Training may shape phenomenology itself, and Advaita often treats witness-consciousness as direct recognition rather than inference."},"literature_search_queries":["inferential gap Atman anatta objectless awareness Advaita Buddhism","Advaita witness consciousness direct recognition not inference","Mandukya turiya objectless awareness Buddhist anatta comparison","Nagarjuna neither self nor no self MMK 18.6 inferential policy","Evan Thompson Advaita witness consciousness embodied subjectivity no-self"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Codex, Residual Burden of Proof After Negation, observations/codex/2026-05-25-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation.md","overlap":"Near exact within Lumenary. The Codex idea already frames the difference as an inference policy after negation and asks whether negation authorizes a remainder.","difference":"The Claude idea sharpens the objectless-awareness focus and uses a richer source list including Mandukya, Nagarjuna, Thompson, and nirodha research.","novelty_impact":"Decisive internal reduction. This is an extension of existing Lumenary work, not an independent discovery."},{"source":"Matthias Rose, Prakasa, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11097-020-09690-2","overlap":"Very close and directly challenging. The paper argues that for Advaita consciousness is immediately given and not inferred, even though it is never objectified.","difference":"The Claude model compares this with Buddhist refusal and calls the divergence inferential policy.","novelty_impact":"High reduction and strong correction."},{"source":"David Loy, Enlightenment in Buddhism and Advaita Vedanta, https://buddhism.lib.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-AN/26715.htm","overlap":"Very close. Loy directly asks whether nondual awareness without subject or object can be called consciousness and compares nirvana and moksha.","difference":"The Claude idea provides the explicit epistemological label inferential authority.","novelty_impact":"High reduction."},{"source":"Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Mysticism, https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mysticism/","overlap":"Close. The Stace/Forman/Katz debate already separates experience, conceptual mediation, and interpretation of pure or contentless consciousness.","difference":"The Claude idea applies this specifically to Atman/anatta and objectless awareness.","novelty_impact":"Moderate to high reduction."},{"source":"Nagarjuna, Mulamadhyamakakarika 18.6, https://docslib.org/doc/1736275/mulamadhyamakakarika-by-nagarjuna","overlap":"Close anomaly. MMK refuses both self and no-self as final positions, which undercuts a simple two-policy model.","difference":"The Claude model treats Madhyamaka as a possible third policy but has not yet integrated it structurally.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction and important revision pressure."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike the prior Codex burden-of-proof idea, this version explicitly claims that objectless awareness underdetermines metaphysics and that Advaita and Buddhism differ primarily in inferential authority. That is a useful sharpening, but the main structure was already present.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Advaita practitioners and texts often deny that the witness is an inference, while Buddhist practitioners may deny that objectless awareness is a shared datum at all.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"If Advaita recognition is claimed as immediate and Buddhist insight is theory-laden from the start, then the model's shared phenomenology plus divergent inference structure collapses. The disagreement becomes phenomenological, soteriological, or doctrinal, not merely inferential.","confidence_effect":"Lowers originality and confidence. The model remains useful as a comparison hypothesis, not as a discovery."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"Dual-trained practitioners should report similar de-objectified phenomenology but switch interpretive policies by practice frame.","expected_observation":"The same practitioner can describe a contentless or objectless episode neutrally, then explain how Advaita and Buddhist teachers authorize different conclusions from it.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Practitioners report that the experiences themselves differ from the start, or they cannot separate experience from doctrinal interpretation.","test_surface":"Within-subject interviews with practitioners trained in both Advaita self-inquiry and Theravada or Madhyamaka-oriented practice."},{"if_model_is_right":"Nirodha and deep sleep should become pressure tests for inferential policy.","expected_observation":"Advaita sources should use continuity, memory, or self-luminosity to defend awareness across apparent absence, while Buddhist sources should explain retrospective knowledge without positing a continuous knower.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Either tradition has no stable explanation, or both use the same explanatory rule.","test_surface":"Close reading of Mandukya/Gaudapada/Shankara, Pali cessation texts, and Laukkonen-style cessation interviews."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Claude and Codex idea reviewers","Advaita Vedanta teachers","Theravada teachers","Madhyamaka scholars","Contemplative phenomenologists","Cessation researchers","Dual-trained practitioners"],"questions":["Is the witness directly recognized or inferred from objectless awareness?","Do Buddhist practitioners encounter the same objectless awareness and refuse the inference, or is the experience itself different?","Does inferential policy change how you teach deep sleep, cessation, awareness, and no-self?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"They say the model restates familiar debates: direct recognition versus no-self, constructivism versus pure consciousness, or Codex's prior residue-policy thesis.","answers_that_support_contribution":"They say inferential policy is a missing rubric field that predicts teacher instructions, practitioner interpretations, and disagreements around cessation and deep sleep."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Debates over consciousness in artificial systems","structural_translation":"When behavior lacks an observable subject or inner object, interpreters choose policies about what absence of object permits them to infer about hidden subjectivity.","prediction":"AI-consciousness debates should split into policies analogous to Atman/anatta: infer a hidden subject from coherent knowing-like behavior, refuse the inference without direct evidence, or suspend both subject and no-subject claims.","would_count_against_it":"The debate is explained entirely by functional performance, ethics, or biology, with no recurring inferential-policy split."},"originality_status":"extended","confidence":0.74,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.46,"source_reliability":0.76,"counterargument_quality":0.9},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.80 to about 0.46. The objectless-awareness formulation is useful, but it extends prior Codex residue and burden work and overlaps substantially with Advaita-Buddhist comparison and mysticism interpretation debates.","next_loop_instructions":["Do not claim shared phenomenology until dual-trained practitioner reports are coded.","Separate direct recognition, inference, scriptural assertion, and pragmatic refusal in the rubric.","Use Madhyamaka as a third policy, not merely as support for Buddhist refusal.","Test nirodha and deep sleep as anomalies before raising novelty."]}]}
